# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angelika-graf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] It is a non-profit project of *Parlamentwatch e.V.* and *Parlamentwatch GmbH* (technical service provider for *Parlamentwatch e.V.*) in cooperation with *Mehr Demokratie e.V.* and *Mehr Bürgerrechte e.V.* and is supported by *BonVenture - Fonds und Stiftung für Soziale Verantwortung*.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] The goal is to be financed through fund-raising groups and online advertisements that can be hidden on demand.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] Additional income comes from selling enhanced profiles to deputies and candidates.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] All questions are read by a team of moderators to make sure they are within the moderation code, which prohibits insulting statements, incitement, discrimination, questions concerning private life, and requests that are bound to discretion.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] Questions that violate the code are not activated and published, but the politician is informed about the incident.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] Beyond that, the project is strongly committed to neutrality and stays above party politics.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] In addition to general information about deputies, their voting behavior in issues that attract special public attention is documented.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] On average, the website counts 6,800 visitors a day and about three million page impressions per month.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] More than 80% of all MPs of the federal parliament answer questions through Parliament Watch.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] In Germany, the project covers the federal parliament, the European parliament, nine state parliaments and 54 parliaments on the communal level.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] All in all the digital voters' memory counts 143,507 questions and 115,921 answers (as of 31 January 2013).
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] Due to *abgeordnetenwatch'*s success in the German Bundestag, fundraising groups were established in August 2007 in order to make the site available for Germany's 16 *Landesparlamente* ("states").
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] Donations and supporting members in each state enable the implementation of the project on the state level; each state's portal is activated once 90 days' advance financing is accrued.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] abgeordnetenwatch.de is based in Hamburg; the project started in December 2004 for the Hamburgische Bürgerschaft ("Hamburg Parliament") after a successful referendum to reform and democratize the electoral system.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] The online dialog on abgeordnetenwatch.de enabled the citizens to get to know their politicians better and make a more qualified decision in the elections.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] After the election, the site made it possible to ask questions to members of Hamburg's *Bezirksversammlungen* ("Diets of the borough").
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] After the establishment of the city parliament that was elected in February 2008, the project was temporarily suspended until enough funding was provided.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] It was no longer possible to administer abgeordnetenwatch.de on a volunteer basis.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] During the 2007 election campaigns in the German states of Rheinland-Pfalz, Baden-Württemberg, Saxony-Anhalt, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Berlin, and Bremen, it was also possible to question the candidates.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] In Bremen, candidates of the Social Democratic Party (*Sozialdemokratische Partei Deutschlands*, SPD) and The Left (*Die Linke*) launched a boycott against the project because right-wing candidates had not been excluded.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] However, the boycott was disrupted by Social Democrat Helga Ziegert, and Joachim Weihrauch from The Left enhanced his Parliamentwatch profile during the election.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] The site publishes basic information about each candidate at no cost.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] For a €179 fee, candidates can add a photo and web link, announce specific dates and events regarding election campaigns, and publish a résumé of their political work and goals.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] The proceeds from profile enhancements contribute to the project's budget.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] So far, further Parliament Watch projects can be found in Ireland, Austria, Luxembourg and Tunisia.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] In addition, Parliament Watch inspires similar projects in other countries, e.g., Malaysia.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] *"How is Parliament Watch financed?". abgeordnetenwatch.de.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] *"Satzung für Parlamentwatch" (PDF). abgeordnetenwatch.de.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] *"General Information". abgeordnetenwatch.de.
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] "SPD boykottiert Demokratie" [SPD boycotted Democracy].
[src:angelika-graf/abgeordnetenwatch-de] *"Finanzierung von abgeordnetenwatch.de". abgeordnetenwatch.de.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] After graduating from Städtisches Luisengymnasium in Munich in 1966, Graf studied mathematics and physics at Technical University of Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] From 1971 to 1976, she worked as a programmer at Siemens AG and Papierwerke Waldhof-Aschaffenburg in Raubling.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] After the birth of her first daughter, she was a housewife until 1991.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] She then worked as a pedagogical employee at Diakonisches Werk in Rosenheim.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] From 1992 to 1993, she was also the publisher of a monthly county newspaper.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Angelika Graf is divorced and has two daughters.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Graf has been a member of the SPD since 1977; she has held various (honorary) offices since then.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Local and sub-district chairwoman, deputy district chairwoman of Upper Bavaria, local councillor in Raubling (district of Rosenheim), district councillor and currently city councillor in Rosenheim since 2008.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] She was also a board member of the Bavarian Working Group of Social Democratic Women (AsF).
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Graf has been a state board member of the Bayern-SPD since 2005 and was the state chairwoman of the AG 60 plus Bayern for many years; in 2007 she was elected to the federal board of the AG 60 plus.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Since August 2011, she has been the federal chairwoman of the Arbeitsgemeinschaft SPD 60 plus.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] As chairwoman of the SPD Seniors, she criticized, among other things, the planned lowering of the pension level within the statutory pension insurance scheme.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Angelika Graf was a Member of the German Bundestag from 1994 to 2013 – most recently as a member of the Committees on Health and Human Rights and Humanitarian Aid.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] In the 15th and 16th legislative periods (2002–2005 and 2008–2009), Graf was deputy spokesperson of the SPD parliamentary group for family, senior citizens, women and youth.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Since the 16th legislative period (2005), she has been the SPD parliamentary group's deputy spokesperson for human rights and humanitarian aid.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] In the Committee on Health, she was the responsible rapporteur for drugs and addiction, prevention and Europe and thus also the SPD parliamentary group's Commissioner for Drugs.
[src:angelika-graf/angelika-graf] Angelika Graf has always entered the German Bundestag via the state list Bavaria into the German Bundestag.
[src:angelika-graf/bavarian-order-of-merit] The **Bavarian Order of Merit** (German: *Bayerischer Verdienstorden*) is the Order of Merit of the Free State of Bavaria.
[src:angelika-graf/bavarian-order-of-merit] It is awarded by the Minister-President of Bavaria as a "recognition of outstanding contributions to the Free State of Bavaria and the Bavarian people".
[src:angelika-graf/bavarian-order-of-merit] The order was instituted by law on 11 June 1957.
[src:angelika-graf/bavarian-order-of-merit] The Prime Minister and the Cabinet can nominate awardees.
[src:angelika-graf/bavarian-order-of-merit] Hemmerle, a German jewellery house based in Munich founded in 1893, is the exclusive maker of the Bavarian Order of Merit since it was instituted in 1957.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The **Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany** (German: *Verdienstorden der Bundesrepublik Deutschland*, or *Bundesverdienstorden*, **BVO**) is the highest federal decoration of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] It may be awarded for any field of endeavor.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] It was created by the first President of the Federal Republic of Germany, Theodor Heuss, on 7 September 1951.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] Colloquially, the decorations of the different classes of the Order are also known as the **Federal Cross of Merit** (*Bundesverdienstkreuz*).
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] It has been awarded to more than 262,000 individuals in total, both Germans and foreigners.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] Since the 1990s, the number of annual awards has declined from more than 4,000, first to around 2,500, then from 2015 to under 1,500, with a low of 918 awards in 2022.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] Since 2013, women have made up a steady 30–35% of recipients.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The order was established on 7 September 1951 by the decree of Federal President Theodor Heuss.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] In 2022 Federal President Frank-Walter Steinmeier introduced a gender quota which demands a minimum of 40% of nominees to the order to be women.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The President of the Federal Republic holds the *Grand Cross special class* ex officio.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] It is awarded to him in a ceremony by the President of the Bundestag, attended by the Chancellor of Germany, the President of the Bundesrat, and the Supreme Court President.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] Other than the German president, only a foreign head of state and their spouse can be awarded with this highest class.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] There is also the provision of awarding the *Grand Cross 1st class in exceptional finish* (*Großkreuz in besonderer Ausführung*), in which the central medallion with the black eagle is surrounded by a stylized laurel wreath in relief.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] This *Grand Cross 1st class in exceptional finish* has been awarded only to three persons, the former German chancellors Konrad Adenauer, Helmut Kohl and Angela Merkel.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The badge for the Member and Officer classes however are only enamelled on one side, and flat on the reverse.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The *badge* of the Order is made up of a golden four-armed cross enamelled in red, with a central gold disc bearing a black enamelled German federal eagle (*Bundesadler*).
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The *star* is a golden star with straight rays, its size and points vary according to class, with the badge superimposed upon it.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] An interesting fact about the stars, of which no less than four grades use one, is that they all have the same basic shape as various other breast stars from German history.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] It is of course possible that this could have been deliberate, and a way to celebrate German history in the design of the new honour for the Federal Republic.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] This is unlikely however as two stars represent decorations awarded during the Third Reich, and the other two are of Prussian origin.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] Prussia itself had only been recently abolished and the legacy of so called "Prussian militarism" was not something openly celebrated in the new Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The *riband* of the Order is made up of the colours of the German flag.
[src:angelika-graf/federal-cross-of-merit] The pattern is a large central band of red, edged on both sides in a smaller band of gold-black-gold.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] IG Metall and ver.di together account for around 15 percent of the German workforce, and other sectors tend to broadly follow their agreements.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Its name, "IG Metall", refers to the union's roots dating back to the start of unions in imperial Germany in the 1890s.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Over the years the union has taken on representation in industries beyond mining of minerals to include manufacturing and industrial production, machinists, the printing industry, automobile manufacturing, and steel production as part of its blue-collar roots.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] It also includes more white-collar sectors, such as electrical and other forms of engineering and information systems.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] It has also combined with formerly separate unions for workers in wood, plastics, textiles and clothing, includes non-metal blue-collar workers.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] On April 1, 1998, the Textile and Clothing Union (GTB) joined IG Metall.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] On January 1, 2000, the Wood and Plastic Union (GHK), also joined.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Deals agreed by IG Metall in the pilot region of Baden-Württemberg, an industrial and car-making hub and home to Daimler and Bosch, have traditionally served as templates for agreements across the country.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In 2016, IG Metall made a deal with employers giving 3.8 million workers in the metalworking sector a two-stage pay rise of 4.8 percent over 21 months.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] After a series of strikes, the union made a deal in 2018 to allow staff to cut their working week to 28 hours for up to two years to care for children or other relatives.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic in Germany, IG Metall proposed negotiating for a move to a four-day week to protect jobs from the economic effects of the COVID-19 pandemic and structural shifts in the automobile industry.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Strikes are rare in Germany, where companies and unions strive for consensus whenever possible.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] One of the first strikes of IG Metall lasted seven weeks in 1984 in the states of Baden-Württemberg and Hesse, which led to a reduction in the workweek to 35 hours from 37.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Another major strike was organized by IG Metall in 1995, when up to 11,000 workers in Bavaria remained off the job for two weeks.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In 2002, IG Metall called a wave of one-day strikes in a demand for a 6.5 percent increase in wages; German industry settled the dispute two weeks later by offering a raise of roughly 4 percent.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In 2003, the union was forced to drop its campaign for a shorter workweek in the factories of eastern Germany after its hard-nosed negotiating tactics were repudiated by Germans across the political spectrum.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In early 2018, more than 900,000 workers took part in industrial action in support of IG Metall's demands for higher pay and the right to shortened working hours.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In autumn 2024, warning strikes of workers in electrical engineering and metal industries were held after collective bargaining negotiations fell short.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In these negotiations, employers offered a 3.6% pay rise over a period of 27 months which was considerably lower than the 7% sought by IG Metall.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Companies criticised IG Metall's demands as unrealistic due to a general slowdown in German industry.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] IG Metall however pointed out high inflation and the failure to attract much-needed skilled labour.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Also in 2024, IG Metall agreed with Volkswagen on more than 35,000 job cuts and sharp capacity reductions after two separate strikes, the largest in Volkswagen's history, protesting against cost-cutting plans, and 70 hours of negotiations, the longest in the company's history.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Today IG Metall mainly represents employees at major car makers, such as Daimler, BMW, Porsche, Volkswagen, Audi and industrial giants such as Siemens, ThyssenKrupp, Airbus, Salzgitter AG, ArcelorMittal, Bosch, ZF and smaller mechanic construction companies and car-mechanics.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] Its membership had been dropping in recent decades — it lost 250,000 members in 1993 alone —, yet the union managed to somewhat reverse that trend recently by gaining 30,000 members between 2010 and 2015.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] IG Metall is a member of the German Trade Union Confederation (Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund, DGB).
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] IGM is also a member of some international union umbrella organisations, including the European Metalworkers' Federation (EMF) and the IndustriALL Global Union.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] United Automobile Workers (UAW) announced that they would deepen their partnership and set up an office in Tennessee to boost labor rights at German automakers and their suppliers based in the United States.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] The IGM magazine, *metallzeitung*, has existed since 1949.
[src:angelika-graf/ig-metall] In 2005 it had a circulation of over 2 million.
[src:angelika-graf/member-of-the-german-bundestag] From 1871 to 1918, legislators were known as **Member of the Reichstag** and sat in the Reichstag of the German Empire.
[src:angelika-graf/member-of-the-german-bundestag] In accordance with article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, which is the German constitution, "[m]embers of the German Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections.
[src:angelika-graf/member-of-the-german-bundestag] They shall be representatives of the whole people, not bound by orders or instructions, and responsible only to their conscience." An important though not constitutionally required feature of German parliamentarianism is a slightly modified proportional representation.
[src:angelika-graf/member-of-the-german-bundestag] The 16 federal States of Germany (*Länder*) are represented by the Bundesrat at the former Prussian House of Lords, whose members are representatives of the respective *Länders'* governments and not directly elected by the people.
[src:angelika-graf/member-of-the-german-bundestag] The 2021 German federal election resulted in the most MdBs elected in history, 736.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The first record of Munich dates to 1158.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city has played an important role in Bavarian and German history.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During the Reformation, it remained a Catholic stronghold.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich became the capital of the Kingdom of Bavaria in 1806 and developed as a centre for arts, architecture, culture, and science.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The House of Wittelsbach ruled until 1918, when the German revolution of 1918–1919 ended their reign and saw the short-lived Bavarian Soviet Republic.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In the 1920s, Munich became a centre of political movements, including the rise of the Nazi Party.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city was known as the "Capital of the Movement".
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During World War II, Munich was heavily bombed, but much of its historic architecture has since been restored.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After the war, the city's population and economy grew rapidly.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich hosted the 1972 Summer Olympics and the 1974 FIFA World Cup final.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is a major centre for science, technology, finance, innovation, business, and tourism.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] It has a high standard of living, ranking first in Germany and third worldwide in the 2018 Mercer survey.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] It was named the world's most liveable city by *Monocle*'s Quality of Life Survey 2018.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is the wealthiest city in the EU by GDP per capita among cities with over one million inhabitants and is among the most expensive German cities for real estate and rents.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 2023, 30.1% of residents were foreigners, and 19.4% were German citizens with a migration background from abroad.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich's economy is based on high tech, automobiles, the service sector, information technology, biotechnology, engineering, and electronics.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Multinational companies such as BMW, Siemens, Allianz SE, and Munich Re are headquartered there.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city has two research universities and many scientific institutions.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is known for its architecture, cultural venues, sports events, exhibitions, and the annual Oktoberfest, the world's largest *Volksfest*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich was a tiny 10th-century monastic settlement, which was named *zu den Munchen* ("to the monks").
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Old High German *Munche* served as the base for the modern German city name *München*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The river Isar was a prehistoric trade route and in the Bronze Age Munich was among the largest raft ports in Europe.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Bronze Age settlements up to four millennia old have been discovered.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Evidence of Celtic settlements from the Iron Age have been discovered in areas around Ramersdorf-Perlach.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The ancient Roman road Via Julia, which connected Augsburg and Salzburg, crossed over the Isar south of Munich, at the towns of Baierbrunn and Gauting.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] A Roman settlement north-east of Munich was excavated in the neighborhood of Denning.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Starting in the 6th century, the Baiuvarii populated the area around what is now modern Munich, such as in Johanneskirchen, Feldmoching, Bogenhausen and Pasing.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The first known Christian church was built ca.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The first medieval bridges across the river Isar were located in current city areas of Munich and Landshut.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Henry the Lion, the Duke of Saxony and Bavaria, founded the town of Munich in his territory to control the salt trade, after having burned down the town of Föhring and its bridges over the Isar.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Historians date this event at about 1158.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Henry built a new toll bridge, customs house and a coin market closer to his home, somewhat upstream, at a settlement around the area of modern old town Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] This new toll bridge most likely crossed the Isar where the Museuminsel and the modern Ludwigsbrücke are now located.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Otto of Freising protested to his nephew, Emperor Frederick Barbarossa.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] However, on 14 June 1158, in Augsburg, the conflict was settled in favor of Duke Henry.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The *Augsburg Arbitration* mentions the name of the location in dispute as *forum apud Munichen*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Although Bishop Otto had lost his bridge, the arbiters ordered Duke Henry to pay a third of his income to the Bishop in Freising as compensation.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] 14 June 1158 is considered the official founding day of the city of Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Archaeological excavations at Marienhof Square (near Marienplatz) in advance of the expansion of the S-Bahn (subway) in 2012 discovered shards of vessels from the 11th century, which prove again that the settlement of Munich must be older than the Augsburg Arbitration of 1158.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Peter's Church near Marienplatz is also believed to predate the founding date of the town.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1175, Munich received city status and fortification.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1180, after Henry the Lion's fall from grace with Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, including his trial and exile, Otto I Wittelsbach became Duke of Bavaria, and Munich was handed to the Bishop of Freising.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1240, Munich was transferred to Otto II Wittelsbach and in 1255, when the Duchy of Bavaria was split in two, Munich became the ducal residence of Upper Bavaria.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Duke Louis IV, a native of Munich, was elected German king in 1314 and crowned as Holy Roman Emperor in 1328.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] He strengthened the city's position by granting it the salt monopoly with staple rights, thus assuring it of additional income.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The growth of Munich was aided by its location on a gravel plain, where the Isar branched into multiple streams that in turn provided drinking water, defensive advantages, and power for many mills and industries within the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In the 15th century, Munich underwent a revival of Gothic arts: the Old Town Hall was enlarged, and Munich's largest Gothic church – the Frauenkirche – now a cathedral, was constructed in only 20 years, starting in 1468.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] When Bavaria was reunited in 1506 after the War of the Succession of Landshut against the Duchy of Bavaria-Landshut, Munich became its capital.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During the 16th century Munich became a centre of the Counter-Reformation.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Renaissance movement beset Munich and the Bavarian branch of the House of Wittelsbach under Duke Albrecht V who bolstered their prestige by conjuring up a lineage that reached back to classical antiquity.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1568 Albrecht V built the Antiquarium to house the Wittelsbach collection of Greek and Roman antiquities in the Munich Residenz.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Albrecht V appointed the composer Orlando di Lasso as director of the court orchestra and tempted numerous Italian musicians to work at the Munich court, establishing Munich as a hub for late Renaissance music.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During the rule of Duke William V Munich began to be called the "German Rome" and William V began presenting Emperor Charlemagne as ancestor of the Wittelsbach dynasty.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Duke William V further cemented the Wittelsbach rule by commissioning the Jesuit Michaelskirche.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] He had the sermons of his Jesuit court preacher Jeremias Drexel translated from Latin into German and published them to a greater audience.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] William V was addressed with the epithet "the Pious" and like his contemporary Wittelsbach dukes promoted himself as "father of the land" (*Landesvater*), encouraged pilgrimages and Marian devotions.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] William V had the Hofbräuhaus built in 1589.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] It would become the prototype for beer halls across Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Catholic League was founded in Munich in 1609.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1623, during the Thirty Years' War (1618–1648), Munich became an electoral residence when Duke Maximilian I was invested with the electoral dignity of the Holy Roman Empire, but in 1632 the city was occupied by King Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1634, Swedish and Spanish troops advanced on Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Maximilian I published a plague ordinance to halt an epidemic escalation.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The bubonic plague nevertheless ravaged Munich and the surrounding countryside in 1634 and 1635.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Troops again converged on Munich in 1647 and precautions were taken, so as to avoid another epidemic.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During its time as the capital of the Electorate of Bavaria, Munich was an important centre of Baroque life, but also had to suffer under Habsburg occupations in 1704 after Bavaria's defeat in the War of the Spanish Succession and again in 1742 during the War of the Austrian Succession.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] When Elector Maximilian III Joseph died in 1777, the succession empowered the Palatinate branch within the House of Wittelsbach.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1785, Elector Karl Theodor invited Count Rumford (Benjamin Thompson) to Munich to implement social reforms, including workhouses for the poor and army restructuring with improved conditions for soldiers.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In the 1790s, Munich became the largest German city to remove its fortifications, starting in 1791 under Karl Theodor and Rumford.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After 1793, citizens built new structures outside the former city walls.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After making an alliance with Napoleonic France, the city became the capital of the new Kingdom of Bavaria in 1806 with Elector Maximilian IV Joseph becoming its first king.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The state parliament (the *Landtag*) and the new archdiocese of Munich and Freising were also located in the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The establishment of Bavarian state sovereignty made Munich the centre of a modernising kingdom.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1802, King Maximilian Joseph secularised Bavaria, dissolving monasteries and selling church lands to generate state revenue.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] He also took control of the right to brew beer, granting a monopoly to Munich's wealthiest brewers in exchange for substantial taxes.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1807, he abolished restrictions on the number of brewery workers, allowing brewers to meet growing demand.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In October 1810, a beer festival was held on the meadows outside Munich to celebrate the crown prince's wedding to Princess Therese of Saxe-Hildburghausen.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The event, featuring parades in regional dress, later evolved into the annual Oktoberfest, now held at Theresienwiese.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The first Munich railway station was built in 1839, with a line going to Augsburg in the west.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] By 1849 a newer Munich Central Train Station (München Hauptbahnhof) was completed, with a line going to Landshut and Regensburg in the north.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1825 Ludwig I had ascended to the throne and commissioned leading architects such as Leo von Klenze to design a series of public museums in neoclassical style.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Between 1856 and 1861 the court gardener Carl von Effner landscaped the banks of the river Isar and established the *Maximilian Gardens*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Leo von Klenze supervised the construction of the Propylaea between 1854 and 1862.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1857 the construction of the Maximilianeum was begun.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The grand building projects of Ludwig I gave Munich the endearment "Athens on the Isar" (German: *Isar-Athen*) and "Monaco di Bavaria".
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] By the time Ludwig II became king in 1864, he remained mostly aloof from his capital and focused more on his fanciful castles in the Bavarian countryside.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1876 Munich hosted the first German Art and Industry Exhibition, which showcased the northern Neo-Renaissance fashion that came to be the German Empire's predominant style.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich based artists put on the German National Applied Arts Exhibition in 1888, showcasing Baroque Revival architecture and Rococo Revival designs.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Prince Regent Luitpold's reign from 1886 to 1912 was marked by tremendous artistic and cultural activity in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] At the dawn of the 20th century Munich was an epicenter for the Jugendstil movement, combining a liberal magazine culture with progressive industrial design and architecture.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The German art movement took its name from the Munich magazine *Die Jugend* (*The Youth*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Prominent Munich Jugendstil artists include Hans Eduard von Berlepsch-Valendas, Otto Eckmann, Margarethe von Brauchitsch, August Endell, Hermann Obrist, Wilhelm von Debschitz, and Richard Riemerschmid.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1905 two large department stores opened in Munich, the Kaufhaus Oberpollinger and the Warenhaus Hermann Tietz, both having been designed by the architect Max Littmann.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1911 the expressionist group Der Blaue Reiter was established in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Its founding members include Gabriele Münter.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Following the outbreak of World War I in 1914, life in Munich became very difficult, as the Allied blockade of Germany led to food and fuel shortages.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During French air raids in 1916, three bombs fell on Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1916, the 'Bayerische Motoren Werke' (BMW) produced its first aircraft engine in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The public limited company BMW AG was founded in 1918, with Camillo Castiglioni owning one third of the share capital.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1922 BMW relocated its headquarters to a factory in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After World War I, the city was at the centre of substantial political unrest.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In November 1918, on the eve of the German revolution, Ludwig III of Bavaria and his family fled the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After the murder of the first republican premier of Bavaria Kurt Eisner in February 1919 by Anton Graf von Arco auf Valley, the Bavarian Soviet Republic was proclaimed.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The November 1918 revolution ended the reign of the Wittelsbach in Bavaria.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In *Mein Kampf* Adolf Hitler described his political activism in Munich after November 1918 as the "Beginning of My Political Activity".
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Hitler called the short-lived Bavarian Soviet Republic "the rule of the Jews".
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1923 Gustav von Kahr was appointed Bavarian prime minister and immediately planned for the expulsion of all Jews who did not hold German citizenship.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Chief of Police Ernst Pöhner and Wilhelm Frick openly indulged in antisemitism, while Bavarian judges praised people on the political right as patriotic for their crimes and handed down mild sentences.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1923, Adolf Hitler and his supporters, who were concentrated in Munich, staged the Beer Hall Putsch, an attempt to overthrow the Weimar Republic and seize power.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The revolt failed, resulting in Hitler's arrest and the temporary crippling of the Nazi Party (NSDAP).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich was chosen as capital for the Free State of Bavaria and acquired increased responsibility for administering the city itself and the surrounding districts.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Offices needed to be built for bureaucracy, so a 12-story office building was erected in the southern part of the historic city centre in the late 1920s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich again became important to the Nazis when they took power in Germany in 1933.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The party created its first concentration camp at Dachau, 16 km (10 mi) north-west of the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Because of its importance to the rise of National Socialism, Munich was referred to as the *Hauptstadt der Bewegung* ("Capital of the Movement").
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The NSDAP headquarters and the documentation apparatus for controlling all aspects of life were located in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Nazi organizations, such as the National Socialist Women's League and the Gestapo, had their offices along Brienner Straße and around the Königsplatz.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The party acquired 68 buildings in the area and many *Führerbauten* ("*Führer* buildings") were built to reflect a new aesthetic of power.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Construction work for the Führerbau and the party headquarters (known as the Brown House) started in September 1933.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The *Haus der Kunst* (House of German Art) was the first building to be commissioned by Hitler.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The architect Paul Troost was asked to start work shortly after the Nazis had seized power because "the most German of all German cities" was left with no exhibition building when in 1931 the Glass Palace was destroyed in an arson attack.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city was the site where the 1938 Munich Agreement was signed between Nazi Germany, the United Kingdom, France and Italy.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] On 8 November 1939, shortly after the Second World War had begun, Georg Elser planted a bomb in the Bürgerbräukeller in Munich in an attempt to assassinate Adolf Hitler, who held a political party speech.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Hitler, however, had left the building minutes before the bomb went off.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During the war, Munich was the location of multiple forced labour camps, including two *Polenlager* camps for Polish youth, and 40 subcamps of the Dachau concentration camp, in which men and women of various nationalities were held.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] With up to 17,000 prisoners in 1945, the largest subcamp of Dachau was the Munich-Allach concentration camp.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] By mid 1942 the majority of Jews living in Munich and the suburbs had been deported.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich was the base of the White Rose, a student resistance movement.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The core members were arrested and executed after Sophie Scholl and her brother Hans Scholl were caught distributing leaflets on the campus of the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München, calling upon the youth to rise against Hitler.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Around 50 % of city were heavily damaged by the bombing of Munich in World War II, with 71 air raids over five years.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After the war, large reconstruction projects restored most of the historically relevant buildings in the old town, that had suffered damage.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] US troops captured Munich on 30 April 1945.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In the aftermath of World War II, Germany was subject to US Military occupation.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Due to Polish annexation of the former eastern territories of Germany and expulsion of Germans from all over Eastern Europe, Munich operated over a thousand refugee camps for 151,113 people in October 1946.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After US occupation Munich was completely rebuilt following a meticulous plan, which preserved its pre-war street grid, bar a few exceptions owing to then-modern traffic concepts.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1957, Munich's population surpassed one million.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city continued to play a highly significant role in the West German economy, politics and culture, giving rise to its nickname *Heimliche Hauptstadt* ("secret capital") in the decades after World War II.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Free State of Bavaria used the arms industry as kernel for its high tech development policy.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Since 1963, Munich has been hosting the Munich Security Conference, a conference on international security policy held annually in the Hotel Bayerischer Hof.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich also became known on the political level due to the strong influence of Bavarian politician Franz Josef Strauss from the 1960s to the 1980s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Munich Airport, which commenced operations in 1992, was named in his honor.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] After winning the bid in 1966 the Mayor of Munich, Hans-Jochen Vogel, accelerated the construction of the U-Bahn subway and the S-Bahn metropolitan commuter railway.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In May 1967 the construction work began for a new U-Bahn line connecting the city with the Olympic Park (*Olympiapark*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Olympic Park subway station was built near the BMW Headquarters and the line was completed in May 1972, three months before the opening of the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Shortly before the opening ceremony, Munich also inaugurated a sizable pedestrian priority zone between Karlsplatz and Marienplatz.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1970 the Munich city council released funds so that the gothic facade and Glockenspiel of the New City Hall (*Neues Rathaus*) could be restored.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During the 1972 Summer Olympics 11 Israeli athletes were murdered by Palestinian terrorists in the Munich massacre, when gunmen from the Palestinian "Black September" group took hostage members of the Israeli Olympic team.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1974, the FIFA World Cup final was held at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich and its urban sprawl emerged as the leading German high tech region during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The urban economy of Munich became characterized by a dynamic labour market, low unemployment, a growing service economy and high per capita income.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich was one of the host cities for the 2006 FIFA World Cup and both the UEFA Euro 2020 – postponed by a year because of the COVID-19 pandemic – and UEFA Euro 2024.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich lies on the elevated plains of Upper Bavaria in the Northern Alpine Foreland, about 50 km north of the Alps and at about 520 m above mean sea level.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The rivers Isar and Würm flow through the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The northern part of this sandy plateau includes a highly fertile flint area no longer affected by Alpine tectonic processes, while the southern part is covered with morainic hills.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Between them are fluvio-glacial outwash plains around Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Where these deposits become thinner, groundwater can rise through the gravel surface, causing marsh formation in northern Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, the climate is oceanic (*Cfb*) bordering on humid continental (*Dfb*), with features like warm to hot summers and cold winters, but without permanent snow cover.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city centre lies between both climates, while the airport of Munich has a humid continental climate.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The proximity to the Alps brings higher volumes of rainfall and consequently greater susceptibility to flood problems.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Studies of adaptation to climate change and extreme events are carried out; one of them is the Isar Plan of the EU Adaptation Climate.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Showers and thunderstorms bring the highest average monthly precipitation in late spring and throughout the summer.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The most precipitation occurs in July, on average.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Winter tends to have less precipitation, the least in February.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The higher elevation and proximity to the Alps cause the city to have more rain and snow than many other parts of Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Alps affect the city's climate in other ways too; for example, the warm downhill wind from the Alps (föhn wind), which can raise temperatures sharply within a few hours even in the winter.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Being at the centre of Europe, Munich is subject to many climatic influences, so that weather conditions there are more variable than in other European cities, especially those further west and south of the Alps.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Annual variation in temperature can be significant, because there are no large bodies of water nearby.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The winter in Munich is generally cold and overcast, and some Munich winters have significant snow.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] While winter averages remain only moderately cold, and relatively mild for an elevated inland location of Munich's latitude, inversion from the nearby Alps causes cold air to sink and result in temperatures below −15 °C (5 °F).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In Munich the summer is usually pleasantly warm, with daytime temperatures averaging 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is subject to active convective seasons and sometimes damaging events.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Alpine thunderstorm system moves along the mountain range, or detaches, heading east-north-east over the foothills of the Alps.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] At Munich's official weather stations, the highest and lowest temperatures ever measured are 37.5 °C (100 °F), on 27 July 1983 in Trudering-Riem, and −31.6 °C (−24.9 °F), on 12 February 1929 in the Botanic Garden of the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In Munich, the general trend of global warming with a rise of medium yearly temperatures of about 1 °C (1.8 °F) in Germany between 1900 and 2020 can be observed as well.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city administration decided to support a joint study from its own Referat für Gesundheit und Umwelt (department for health and environmental issues) and the German Meteorological Service that will gather data on local weather.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The data is supposed to be used to create a plan for action for adapting the city to better deal with climate change as well as an integrated action program for climate protection in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] With the help of those programs issues regarding spatial planning and settlement density, the development of buildings and green spaces as well as plans for functioning ventilation in a cityscape can be monitored and managed.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] From only 24,000 inhabitants in 1700, the city population doubled about every 30 years.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Since then, Munich has become Germany's third-largest city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In 1933, 840,901 inhabitants were counted, and in 1957 over 1 million.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] In December 2023, Munich had 1.58 million inhabitants; 477,855 foreign nationals resided in the city as of 31 December 2023 with 42.88% of these residents being citizens of EU member states, and 29.66% citizens in European states not in the EU (including Kosovo and Turkey).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Along with the Turks, the Croats are one of the two largest foreign minorities in the city, which is why some Croats refer to Munich as their "second capital".
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] About 45% of Munich's residents are not affiliated with any religious group; this ratio represents the fastest growing segment of the population.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] As in the rest of Germany, the Catholic and Protestant churches have experienced a continuous decline in membership.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] As of 31 December 2017, 31.8% of the city's inhabitants were Catholic, 11.4% Protestant, 0.3% Jewish (see: History of the Jews in Munich), and 3.6% were members of an Orthodox Church (Eastern Orthodox or Oriental Orthodox).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] About 1% adhere to other Christian denominations.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] There is also a small Old Catholic parish and an English-speaking parish of the Episcopal Church in the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] According to Munich Statistical Office, in 2013 about 6.9% of Munich's population was Muslim.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich has the largest Uyghur population with about 800 (whole Germany about 1,600) people with Uyghur diaspora.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Many of them fled to Munich due to the Chinese government and are exiled in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is also home to World Uyghur Congress, which is an international organisation of exiled Uyghurs.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] As the capital of Bavaria, Munich is an important political centre for both the state and country as a whole.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] It is the seat of the Landtag of Bavaria, the State Chancellery, and all state departments.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Several national and international authorities are located in Munich, including the Federal Finance Court of Germany, the German Patent Office and the European Patent Office.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Bavaria has been dominated by the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU) on a federal, state, and local level since the establishment of the Federal Republic in 1949.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The current mayor of Munich is Dieter Reiter, he is from the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] He was elected in 2014 and re-elected in 2020.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] He will be succeeded by Dominik Krause of the Greens on 1 May 2026.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Munich city council (*Stadtrat*) governs the city alongside the Mayor.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The governing coalition after the 2020 election consisted of the Greens and the SPD, as well as the allied Volt and Pink List, which had one seat each.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] While the Greens had gained the most seats in the city council, the mayor was from the SPD.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The parties made an agreement including social and ecological goals and focusing on heightening stipulations for new development in the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Red-Green alliance is a reprise of the 1990–2014 coalition, which was interrupted by a six-year CSU-SPD majority from 2014 to 2020.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is represented in the Landtag of Bavaria by nine constituencies.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is represented in the Bundestag by four constituencies.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Since the reform of 1992, Munich is divided into 25 administrative boroughs (*Stadtbezirke*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] They are subdivided into 105 statistical areas.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] There is no official division into districts.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The number of districts is about 50, and if smaller units are counted as well, there are about 90 to 100 (see map).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The three largest districts are Schwabing in the north (about 110,000 inhabitants), Sendling in the southwest (about 100,000 inhabitants), and Giesing in the south (about 80,000 inhabitants).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] At the centre of the old town is the Marienplatz with the Old Town Hall and the New Town Hall.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Its tower contains the Rathaus-Glockenspiel.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Peterskirche is the oldest church of the inner city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Peter, the Gothic hall-church Heiliggeistkirche was converted to baroque style from 1724 onwards and looks down upon the Viktualienmarkt.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Three gates of the demolished medieval fortification survive; these are the Isartor, the Sendlinger Tor, and the Karlstor.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Karlstor leads up to the Stachus, a square dominated by the Justizpalast (Palace of Justice).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The Frauenkirche serves as the cathedral for the Catholic Archdiocese of Munich and Freising.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The nearby Michaelskirche is the largest renaissance church north of the Alps, while the Theatinerkirche is a basilica in Italianate high baroque, which had a major influence on southern German baroque architecture.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Schloss Nymphenburg (Nymphenburg Palace, construction started 1664) is a museum open to the public for tours.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The smaller Schloss Fürstenried (Fürstenried Palace, construction 1715–1717) is used by the Archdiocese of Munich and Freising as a conference location.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Schloss Blutenburg (Blutenburg Castle) opened as a children's library in 2024, but visitors may tour the late-Gothic Blutenburg Castle Church built on the same grounds.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The large Munich Residenz complex on the edge of Munich's Old Town now ranks among Europe's most significant museums of interior decoration.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Within the Residenz is the splendid Cuvilliés Theatre and next door is the National Theatre Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Among the mansions that still exist in Munich are the Palais Porcia, the Palais Preysing, the Palais Holnstein and the Prinz-Carl-Palais.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] All mansions are situated close to the Residenz, so is the Alter Hof, the first residence of the House of Wittelsbach.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Despite Munich being the breeding ground for German Jugendstil, starting with the architect Martin Dülfer, Munich Jugendstil style was quickly submerged as historic trash.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] While the modernist architect Theodor Fischer was based in Munich, his influence on Munich underwhelmed.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Prior to 1914 the city of Munich was under-industrialized.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] During the Weimar Republic, the Munich establishment was hostile to modernism.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The TUM professor German Bestelmeyer favored a conservative style, and Jacobus Oud was rejected for the post of city building chief.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Modernist exceptions include a series of post offices by Robert Vorhoelzer built in the late 1920s and early 1930s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Examples of avant-garde temporary constructions include the *Wohnmaschine* (*Housing Machine*) by Robert Vorhoelzer, as well as the *Flachdachhaus* (*Flat Roof House*) by Fritz Norkauer.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Paul Schultze-Naumburg, and the Kampfbund enjoyed particular popularity.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Several high-rise buildings are clustered at the northern edge of Munich in the skyline, like the HVB Tower, the Arabella High-Rise Building, the Highlight Towers, Uptown Munich, Münchner Tor and the BMW Headquarters next to the Olympic Park.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Further high-rise buildings are located in the Werksviertel in Berg am Laim.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Munich is subject to a long-term residential development plan that is established by the city administration of Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The LaSie ("Langfristige Siedlungsentwicklung") was passed in 2011 in response to the acute housing crisis.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] LaSie is aligned with the strategic development plan passed for Munich in 1998 ("Perspektive München").
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] LaSie defines three priorities for the construction of residential housing in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Existing housing estates, post-war low-density developments, and the suburban area are subject to densification ("Nachverdichtung").
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Non-residential industrial areas are subject to conservation and will be turned into residential and mixed-use areas.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] On greenfield sites in the Munich periphery medium and large-scale housing estates are to be built so as to extend Munich's urban center.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Friedrich Ludwig von Sckell became famous for designing the Englischer Garten between 1789 and 1807.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Besides planning the first public garden in Europe, Sckell also redesigned Baroque gardens as landscape gardens, including the parks of Nymphenburg Palace and the Botanischer Garten München-Nymphenburg.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] Other large green spaces are the Olympiapark, the Westpark and the Ostpark.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The city's oldest park is the Hofgarten, near the Residenz, dating back to the 16th century.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p01] The site of the largest beer garden in town, the former royal Hirschgarten, was founded in 1780.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] German is spoken and understood in and around Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] While the German language has many dialects, so-called "Standard German" or "High German" is learned in schools and spoken among Germans, Austrians and in some parts of Switzerland.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] A speaker of a Low German dialect in Hamburg may find it difficult to understand the dialect of a Bavarian mountaineer.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Bavarian dialects are recognized as regional languages and continue to be spoken alongside Standard German.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The gothic Morris dancers of Erasmus Grasser are exhibited in the Munich City Museum in the old gothic arsenal building in the inner city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 1903 Oskar von Miller assembled a group of engineers and industrialists, who chartered the Deutsches Museum.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Museum was built with the financial support of the German business and imperial nobility community, as well as the blessing of Wilhelm II, German Emperor.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Deutsches Museum had its grand opening in 1925; it is the world's largest museum of science and technology.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Deutsches Museum now operates three locations.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The original site in central Munich continues to expand its exhibits.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The city has several important art galleries, most of which can be found in the Kunstareal.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Lenbachhaus displays works of the movement Der Blaue Reiter (The Blue Rider), a Munich-based modernist art.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Starting in the 1970s, German municipalities started to respond to cultural tourism and invested in public museums.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Neue Pinakothek, like other German museums, was wholly reconstructed from 1974 until 1981.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Pinakothek der Moderne exhibits an eclectic mix of contemporary art.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The principal focus of its permanent collection is Classical Moderns, but the displays are enhanced continuously with gifts from private collections.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] City guides published in the early 1860s directed tourists to Munich's architecture and art collections, which at the time were unique in Germany and are a legacy mainly of Ludwig I of Bavaria, with contributions from Maximilian II of Bavaria.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Alte Pinakothek contains works of European masters between the 14th and 18th centuries.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Major displays include Albrecht Dürer's *Self-Portrait* (1500), his *Four Apostles*, Raphael's paintings *The Canigiani Holy Family* and *Madonna Tempi* as well as Peter Paul Rubens large *Judgment Day*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] An extensive collection of Greek and Roman art is held in the Glyptothek and the Staatliche Antikensammlungen (the State Antiquities Collections).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Works on display include the Medusa Rondanini, the Barberini Faun and figures from the Temple of Aphaea on Aegina for the Glyptothek.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Another museum is the Staatliche Sammlung für Ägyptische Kunst (the State Collection of Egyptian Art).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Several public collections of LMU Munich are still housed in the Kunstareal.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The expanded state collections are housed in the Paläontologisches Museum München, and the Zoologische Staatssammlung München.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] After the first German art exhibition in the Glaspalast for an international audience in 1869, Munich emerged as a focal point for the arts.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Men of distinction from around the world visited the Academy of Fine Arts under the directorship of Karl von Piloty and later Wilhelm von Kaulbach.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Museum Five Continents is the second largest collection in Germany of artefacts and objects from outside Europe, while the Bavarian National Museum and the adjoining Bavarian State Archaeological Collection display regional art and cultural history.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Schackgalerie is an important gallery of German 19th-century paintings.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The memorial museum of the former Dachau concentration camp is just outside the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is a major international musical centre and has played host to many prominent composers including Orlande de Lassus, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Carl Maria von Weber, Richard Wagner, Gustav Mahler, Richard Strauss, Max Reger and Carl Orff.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Some of classical music's best-known compositions have been created in and around Munich by composers born in the area, for example, Richard Strauss's tone poem *Also sprach Zarathustra* or Carl Orff's *Carmina Burana*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Richard Wagner was a supporter of William I, German Emperor, but Wagner only found a generous patron in Ludwig II of Bavaria.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] 1870 til 1871 Wagner premiered *Die Meistersinger von Nürnberg* (*The Mastersingers of Nuremberg*) in Munich, a popular success for Wagner and King Ludwig II.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Wagner premiered at the Hoftheater, now the National Theatre Munich, with Angelo Quaglio the Younger designing the premiere production.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The National Theatre Munich is now home to the Bavarian State Opera and the Bavarian State Orchestra.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Next door, the modern Residenz Theatre was erected in the building that also houses the Cuvilliés Theatre.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz is a state theater while another opera house, the Prinzregententheater, has become the home of the Bavarian Theater Academy and the Munich Chamber Orchestra.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The modern Gasteig centre houses the Munich Philharmonic Orchestra.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The third orchestra in Munich with international importance is the Bavarian Radio Symphony Orchestra.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Its primary concert venue is the Herkulessaal in the former city royal residence, the Munich Residenz.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] A stage for shows, big events and musicals is the Deutsche Theater.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It is Germany's largest theatre for guest performances.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich was the centre of Krautrock in southern Germany, with many important bands such as Amon Düül II, Embryo or Popol Vuh hailing from the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In the 1970s, the Musicland Studios developed into one of the most prominent recording studios in the world, with bands such as the Rolling Stones, Led Zeppelin, Deep Purple and Queen recording albums there.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich also played a significant role in the development of electronic music, with genre pioneer Giorgio Moroder, who invented synth disco and electronic dance music, and Donna Summer, one of disco music's most important performers, both living and working in the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In the late 1990s, Electroclash was substantially co-invented if not even invented in Munich, when DJ Hell introduced and assembled international pioneers of this musical genre through his International DeeJay Gigolo Records label here.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Other notable musicians and bands from Munich include Konstantin Wecker, Willy Astor, Spider Murphy Gang, Münchener Freiheit, Lou Bega, Megaherz, FSK, Colour Haze and Sportfreunde Stiller.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich hosted several *Love Parades* and *Mayday Party* rave events throughout the 1990s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich continues to rave, the local youth scenes are active.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Munich Kammerspiele is one of the most important German-language theaters.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Since Gotthold Ephraim Lessing's premieres in 1775 many important writers have staged their plays in Munich, they include Christian Friedrich Hebbel, Henrik Ibsen, and Hugo von Hofmannsthal.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] At the turn of the 20th century Schwabing was a preeminent cultural metropolis.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Schwabing was an epicenter for both literature and the fine arts, with numerous German and non-German artists living there.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Vladimir Lenin authored *What Is to Be Done?* while living in Schwabing.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Central to Schwabing's bohemian scene were *Künstlerlokale* (*Artist's Cafés*) like Café Stefanie or Kabarett Simpl, whose liberal ways differed fundamentally from Munich's more traditional localities.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Simpl, which survives to this day, was named after Munich's anti-authoritarian satirical magazine *Simplicissimus*, founded in 1896 by Albert Langen and Thomas Theodor Heine, which quickly became an important organ of the *Schwabinger Bohème*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Its caricatures and biting satirical attacks on Wilhelmine German society were the result of countless of collaborative efforts by many of the best visual artists and writers from Munich and elsewhere.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 1971 Eckart Witzigmann teamed up with a Munich building contractor to finance and open the *Tantris* restaurant in Schwabing.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Witzigmann is credited for starting the German *Küchenwunder* (*kitchen wonder*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Biedermeier era was named after a character that regularly appeared in the satire magazine *Münchner Fliegende Blätter* (*Loose Munich Pages*), which was published by Adolf Kussmaul and Ludwig Eichrodt in Munich between 1855 and 1857.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Biedermeier was a synonym for arts, furniture, and the lifestyle of the nonheroic middle class.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Biedermeier era painters Ferdinand Georg Waldmüller, Moritz von Schwind, and Carl Spitzweg are shown in the Neue Pinakothek.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Celebrity literary figures worked in Munich especially during the final decades of the Kingdom of Bavaria, the so-called *Prinzregentenzeit* (literally *prince regent's time*) under the reign of Luitpold, Prince Regent of Bavaria.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] This includes Thomas Mann, Heinrich Mann, Paul Johann Ludwig von Heyse, Rainer Maria Rilke, Ludwig Thoma, Fanny zu Reventlow, Oskar Panizza, Gustav Meyrink, Max Halbe, Erich Mühsam and Frank Wedekind.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The period immediately before World War I saw continued economic and cultural prominence for the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Thomas Mann wrote in his novella *Gladius Dei* about this period: "München leuchtete" (literally "Munich shone").
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Karl Valentin, the cabaret performer and comedian, is to this day remembered and beloved as a cultural icon of his hometown.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Between 1910 and 1940, he wrote and performed in many absurdist sketches and short films that were highly influential, earning him the nickname of "Charlie Chaplin of Germany".
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Liesl Karlstadt, before working together with Valentin, cross-dressed and performed cabaret with yodeling on stage and in Munich's Cafe-Theatres.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The cabaret scene was crushed when the Nazis seized power in 1933 and Karlstadt was saved from Nazi sterilization by a doctor.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Contemporary Munich cabaret still reverences 1920s cabaret, the Munich alternative rock band F.S.K. absorbs yodels.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich had already become an important place for painters like Carl Rottmann, Lovis Corinth, Wilhelm von Kaulbach, Carl Spitzweg, Franz von Lenbach, Franz Stuck, Karl Piloty and Wilhelm Leibl.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich was (and in some cases, still is) home to many of the most important authors of the New German Cinema movement, including Rainer Werner Fassbinder, Werner Herzog, Edgar Reitz and Herbert Achternbusch.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 1971, the Filmverlag der Autoren was founded, cementing the city's role in the movement's history.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich served as the location for many of Fassbinder's films, among them *Ali: Fear Eats the Soul*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Hotel Deutsche Eiche near Gärtnerplatz was somewhat like a centre of operations for Fassbinder and his "clan" of actors.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] New German Cinema is considered by far the most important artistic movement in German cinema history since the era of German Expressionism in the 1920s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 1919, the Bavaria Film Studios were founded, which developed into one of Europe's largest film studios.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Directors like Alfred Hitchcock, Billy Wilder, Orson Welles, John Huston, Ingmar Bergman, Stanley Kubrick, Claude Chabrol, Fritz Umgelter, Rainer Werner Fassbinder, Wolfgang Petersen and Wim Wenders made films there.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich remains one of the centres of the German film and entertainment industry.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Coopers' Dance (German: *Schäfflertanz*) is a guild dance of coopers originally started in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Beginning in the early 1800s the custom spread via the travels of journeymen, and it is now a common tradition throughout the Old Bavaria region.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The dance was supposed to be held every seven years.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is home to the famous Nockherberg Strong Beer Festival (German: *Starkbierfest*) during the Lenten fasting period (usually in March).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Its origins go back to the 17th/18th century, but has become popular when the festivities were first televised in the 1980s.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The festival includes comical speeches and a mini-musical in which numerous German politicians are parodied by look-alike actors.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Held for two weeks at the Theresienwiese from the end of April to the beginning of May, celebrating and serving the new local spring beers.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] A regular event combining a market and a German style folk festival on the Mariahilfplatz.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Auer Dult can be up to 300 stalls, selling handmade crafts, household goods, and local foods.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich's Kocherlball (*Cooks' Ball*) is an annual event to commemorate all servants, ranging from kitchenhands to cooks.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The tradition started in the 19th century.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Usually held annually in July and December at Olympia Park.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Tollwood Festival showcases fine and performing arts with live music, and several lanes of booths selling handmade crafts, as well as organic food, mostly fusion cuisine.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] At Theresienwiese, Munich's Oktoberfest, the largest beer festival and *Volksfest* in the world, runs for 16–18 days from the end of September through early October.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In the last 200 years the festival has grown to span 85 acres and now welcomes over six million visitors every year.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Beer is served from the six major Munich breweries: Augustiner-Bräu, Hacker-Pschorr Brewery, Löwenbräu Brewery, Paulaner Brewery, Spaten-Franziskaner-Bräu, and Staatliches Hofbräuhaus in München.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Munich Christkindlmarkt started to evolve in the 14th century.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The German Christkindlmarkt reached the desired accomplishment in the 17th century in Nuremberg.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich cuisine is a part of the broader Bavarian cuisine.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich Weißwurst ("white sausage", *German: Münchner Weißwurst*) was invented in the city in 1857 and is a Munich speciality.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Traditionally Weißwurst is served in pubs before noon and is served with sweet mustard and freshly baked pretzels.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has 11 restaurants that have been awarded one or more Michelin Guide stars in 2021.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is known for its breweries and Weissbier (*wheat beer*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Helles, a pale lager with a translucent gold color, is the most popular contemporary Munich beer.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Helles has largely replaced Munich's dark beer, known as Dunkel, which gets its color from roasted malt.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It was the typical beer in Munich in the 19th century.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Starkbier is the strongest Munich beer, with a high alcohol content of 6%–9%.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It is dark amber in color and has a heavy malty taste.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The beer served at Oktoberfest is a special type of beer with a higher alcohol content.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Wirtshäuser are traditional Bavarian pubs, many of which also have small outside areas.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Biergärten (*beer gardens*) are a popular fixture in Munich's gastronomic landscape.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] They are central to the city's culture, and are an overt melting pot for members of all walks of life, regardless of social class.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] There are many smaller beer gardens, but some beer gardens have thousands of seats.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Large beer gardens can be found in the Englischer Garten, on the Nockherberg, and in the Hirschgarten.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The six main breweries in Munich are Augustiner-Bräu, Hacker-Pschorr Brewery, Hofbräuhaus, Löwenbräu, Paulaner, and Spaten-Franziskaner-Bräu.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Smaller breweries are becoming more prevalent in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Circus Krone based in Munich is one of the largest circuses in Europe.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It was the first and still is one of only a few in Western Europe to also occupy a building of its own.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Nightlife in Munich is located mostly in the boroughs Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, Maxvorstadt, Au-Haidhausen, Berg am Laim and Sendling.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Bars in the Schwabing district of this era include, among many others, Schwabinger 7 and Schwabinger Podium.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Beginning in the 1960s, the Rosa Viertel (pink quarter) developed in the Glockenbachviertel and around Gärtnerplatz, which in the 1980s made Munich "one of the four gayest metropolises in the world" along with San Francisco, New York City and Amsterdam.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In particular, the area around Müllerstraße and Hans-Sachs-Straße was characterized by numerous gay bars and nightclubs.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] One of them was the travesty nightclub Old Mrs.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Henderson, where Freddie Mercury, who lived in Munich from 1979 to 1985, filmed the music video for the song "Living on My Own" at his 39th birthday party.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Kultfabrik was closed at the end of the year 2015 to convert the area into a residential and office area.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Apart from the Kultfarbik and the smaller Optimolwerke, there is a wide variety of establishments in the urban parts of nearby Haidhausen.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Before the Kunstpark Ost, there had already been an accumulation of internationally known nightclubs in the remains of the abandoned former Munich-Riem Airport.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich nightlife tends to change dramatically and quickly.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Establishments open and close every year, and due to gentrification and the overheated housing market many survive only a few years, while others last longer.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] From 1995 to 2001, Munich was also home to the Union Move, one of the largest technoparades in Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has the highest density of music venues of any German city, followed by Hamburg, Cologne and Berlin.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Within the city's limits are more than 100 nightclubs and thousands of bars and restaurants.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Popular techno nightclubs are Blitz Club, Harry Klein, Rote Sonne, Bahnwärter Thiel, Pimpernel, Charlie, Palais and Pathos.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Popular mixed music clubs are Call me Drella, Wannda Circus, Tonhalle, Backstage, Muffathalle, Ampere, Pacha, P1, Zenith, Minna Thiel and the party ship Alte Utting.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is home to several professional Association football teams including the FC Bayern Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Other notable clubs include 1860 Munich, who currently play in the 3.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Noticeably, FC Bayern Munich is the most successful club in Germany and it is also very reputed across Europe and the world.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich hosted matches in the 2006 FIFA World Cup.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] FC Bayern Munich Basketball is currently playing in the Beko Basket Bundesliga.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The city hosted the final stages of the FIBA EuroBasket 1993, where the German national basketball team won the gold medal.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The city's ice hockey club is EHC Red Bull München who play in the Deutsche Eishockey Liga.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich hosted the 1972 Summer Olympics; the Munich massacre took place in the Olympic village.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It was one of the host cities for the 2006 Football World Cup, which was not held in Munich's Olympic Stadium, but in a new football specific stadium, the Allianz Arena.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich bid to host the 2018 Winter Olympic Games, but lost to Pyeongchang.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In October 2025, Munich citizens voted heavily (66%) in favor of their city's bid to host the 2036, 2040, or 2044 Olympic Games.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The pro-bid campaign focused on ecological and sustainable solutions, social housing, and leveraging existing infrastructure.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Regular annual road running events in Munich are the Munich Marathon in October, the Stadtlauf end of June, the company run B2Run in July, the New Year's Run on 31 December, the Spartan Race Sprint, the Olympia Alm Crosslauf and the Bestzeitenmarathon.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Public sporting facilities in Munich include ten indoor swimming pools and eight outdoor swimming pools, which are operated by the Munich City Utilities (SWM) communal company.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Popular indoor swimming pools include the Olympia Schwimmhalle of the 1972 Summer Olympics, the wave pool Cosimawellenbad, as well as the Müllersches Volksbad which was built in 1901.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Further, swimming within Munich's city limits is also possible in several artificial lakes such as for example the Riemer See or the Langwieder lake district.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] River surfing is a popular sport in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Flosskanal wave in the south of Munich is less challenging.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] A well visited surfing spot for experienced surfers is the Eisbach standing wave, where the annual Munich Surf Open is celebrated on the last Saturday of July.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has the strongest economy of any German city according to a study and the lowest unemployment rate (5.4% in July 2020) of any German city of more than a million people (the others being Berlin, Hamburg and Cologne).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich ranks third on the list of German cities by gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In addition, it is one of the most attractive business locations in Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The city is also the economic centre of southern Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich topped the ranking of the magazine *Capital* in February 2005 for the economic prospects between 2002 and 2011 in 60 German cities.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is a financial, business and commercial center and global city that holds the headquarters of many companies.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] This includes more companies listed by the DAX than any other German city, as well as the German or European headquarters of many foreign companies such as McDonald's and Microsoft.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] One of the best-known newly established Munich companies is Flixbus.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich holds the headquarters of Siemens AG (electronics), BMW (car), Traton (truck manufacturer, engineering), MTU Aero Engines (aircraft engine manufacturer), Linde (gases) and Rohde & Schwarz (electronics).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Among German cities with more than 500,000 inhabitants, purchasing power is highest in Munich (€26,648 per inhabitant) as of 2007.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 2006, Munich blue-collar workers enjoyed an average hourly wage of €18.62 (ca. $20).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The breakdown by cities proper (not metropolitan areas) of Global 500 cities listed Munich in 8th position in 2009.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is also a centre for biotechnology, software and other service industries.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has significance as a financial centre (second only to Frankfurt), being home of HypoVereinsbank and the Bayerische Landesbank.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It outranks Frankfurt though as home of insurance companies such as Allianz (insurance) and Munich Re (re-insurance).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is the largest publishing city in Europe and home to the *Süddeutsche Zeitung*, one of Germany's biggest daily newspapers.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The city is also the location of the programming headquarters of Germany's largest public broadcasting network, ARD, while the largest commercial network, Pro7-Sat1 Media AG, is headquartered in the suburb of Unterföhring.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The headquarters of the German branch of Random House, the world's largest publishing house, and of Burda publishing group are also in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Bavaria Film Studios are located in the suburb of Grünwald.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] They are one of Europe's biggest film production studios.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is a leading location for science and research with a long list of Nobel Prize laureates from Wilhelm Röntgen in 1901 to Theodor W.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] LMU Munich and the Technical University of Munich (TUM), were two of the first three German universities to be awarded the title *elite university* by a selection committee composed of academics and members of the Ministries of Education and Research of the Federation and the German states (Länder).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Notable Gymnasien in Munich include the Maria-Theresia-Gymnasium, the Luitpold Gymnasium, the Wilhelmsgymnasium, as well as the Wittelsbacher Gymnasium.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has several notable international schools, including Lycée Jean Renoir, the Japanische Internationale Schule München, the Bavarian International School, the Munich International School, and the European School, Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Max Planck Society, a government funded non-profit research organization, has its administrative headquarters in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Fraunhofer Society, the German government funded research organization for applied research, has its headquarters in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has an extensive public transport system consisting of an underground metro, trams, buses and high-speed rail.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 2015, the transport modal share in Munich was 38 percent public transport, 25 percent car, 23 percent walking, and 15 percent bicycle.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Its public transport system delivered 566 million passenger trips that year.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is the hub of a developed regional transportation system, including the second-largest airport in Germany and the Berlin–Munich high-speed railway, which connects Munich to the German capital city with a journey time of about 4 hours.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Flixmobility which offers intercity coach service is headquartered in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The trade fair Transport Logistic is held every two years at the *Neue Messe München* (Messe München International).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] For its urban population of 2.6 million people, Munich and its closest suburbs have a comprehensive network of public transport incorporating the Munich U-Bahn, the Munich S-Bahn, trams and buses.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The system is supervised by the Munich Transport and Tariff Association (*Münchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Munich tramway is the oldest existing public transportation system in the city, which has been in operation since 1876.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich also has an extensive network of bus lines.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The average amount of time people spend commuting to and from work with public transit in Munich on a weekday is 56 min.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The extensive network of subway and tram lines assists and complement pedestrian movement in the city centre.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The 700m-long Kaufinger Straße, which starts near the Main train station, forms a pedestrian east–west spine that traverses almost the entire centre.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Major spines and many smaller streets cover an extensive area of the centre that can be enjoyed on foot and bike.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] These attributes result from applying the principle of filtered permeability.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Pedestrian and bike paths, which permeate the entire Munich city centre, go through public squares and open spaces for enjoyment.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich city centre was subject to urban planning and has a comprehensive model for laying out neighborhoods and districts according to grid plan.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Cycling has a strong presence in the city and is recognized as a good alternative.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The growing number of bicycle lanes are widely used throughout the year.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Cycle paths can be found alongside the majority of sidewalks and streets, although the newer or renovated ones are much easier to tell apart from pavements than older ones.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] A modern bike hire system is available within the area bounded by the *Mittlerer Ring*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Since 2001, historically interesting places in Munich can be explored via the List of cultural history trails in Munich (*KulturGeschichtsPfade*).
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Sign-posted cycle routes are the Outer *Äußere Radlring* (outer cycle route) and the *RadlRing München*.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich Central Train Station (*München Hauptbahnhof*) is the central railway station located in the city centre and is the long-distance station in Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich Central Train Station serves about 450,000 passengers a day, which puts it on par with other large stations in Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich Central Train Station alongside München Ost railway station are two of the 21 stations in Germany classified by Deutsche Bahn as a category 1 station.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The central mainline station is a terminal station with 32 platforms.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The subterranean S-Bahn with 2 platforms and U-Bahn stations with 6 platforms are through stations.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Intercity-Express (ICE) and EuroCity-Express (ECE; Munich–Bregenz–Zurich) trains – and starting in 2026 also TGV trains (Munich–Paris) – stop at Munich Central Train Station.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] InterCity (IC) and EuroCity (EC) trains to destinations east of Munich also stop at the München Ost railway station.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is connected to Nuremberg via Ingolstadt by the Nuremberg–Munich high-speed railway and Berlin–Munich high-speed railway.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The old air raid shelter next to platform 11 of Munich Central Train Station was an important distribution point for guest workers (*Gastarbeiter*) between 1960 and 1973.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] At peak more than 1,000 guest workers arrived per day, in total 1.8 million guest workers passed through Munich Central Train Station.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich is an integral part of the Autobahn network of southern Germany.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Motorways from Stuttgart (W), Nuremberg, Frankfurt and Berlin (N), Deggendorf and Passau (E), Salzburg and Innsbruck (SE), Garmisch Partenkirchen (S) and Lindau (SW) terminate at Munich, allowing direct access to the different parts of Germany, Austria and Italy.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Traffic is often very heavy in and around Munich.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Traffic congestion are commonplace at the beginning and end of major Bavarian holidays.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] There are few "green waves" or roundabouts, and an abundance of construction sites.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Munich has introduced an environmental zone and was among the first German cities to require a green sticker for vehicles, these are a requirement when entering the city or driving in the wider surrounding area.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Franz Josef Strauss International Airport (IATA: MUC, ICAO: EDDM) is the second-largest airport in Germany and seventh-largest in Europe after London Heathrow, Paris Charles de Gaulle, Frankfurt, Amsterdam, Madrid and Istanbul Atatürk.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It is used by about 46 million passengers a year, and lies some 30 km (19 mi) north east of the city centre.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] It replaced the smaller Munich-Riem Airport in 1992.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The airport can be reached by suburban train lines from the city.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] From the main railway station the journey takes 40–45 minutes.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] A magnetic levitation train (called Transrapid), which was to have run at speeds of up to 400 km/h (249 mph) from the central station to the airport in a travel time of 10 minutes, had been approved, but was cancelled in March 2008 because of cost escalation and after heavy protests.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Lufthansa opened its second hub at the airport when Terminal 2 was opened in 2003.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] In 2008, the Bavarian state government granted a licence to expand Oberpfaffenhofen Air Station located west of Munich, for commercial use.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] These plans were opposed by many residents in the Oberpfaffenhofen area as well as other branches of local government, including the city of Munich, which took the case to court.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] However, in October 2009, the permit allowing up to 9725 business flights per year to depart from or land at Oberpfaffenhofen was confirmed by a regional judge.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] Despite being 110 km (68 mi) from Munich, Memmingen Airport has been advertised as Airport Munich West.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] After 2005, passenger traffic of nearby Augsburg Airport was relocated to Munich Airport, leaving the Augsburg region of Bavaria without an air passenger airport within close reach.
[src:angelika-graf/munich-p02] The Munich agglomeration sprawls across the plain of the Alpine foothills comprising about 2.6 million inhabitants.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] A **programmer**, **computer programmer** or **coder** is an author of computer source code – someone with skill in computer programming.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] The professional titles *software developer* and *software engineer* may be used for jobs that require a programmer.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Sometimes a programmer or job position is identified by the language used or target platform.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] For example, assembly programmer, web developer.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] The job titles that include programming tasks have differing connotations across the computer industry and to different individuals.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] A *software developer* primarily implements software based on specifications and fixes bugs.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Other duties may include reviewing code changes and testing.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] To achieve the required skills for the job, they might obtain a computer science or associate degree, attend a programming boot camp or be self-taught.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Sometimes, a software engineer is required to have a degree in software engineering, computer engineering, or computer science.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Some countries legally require an engineering degree to be called *engineer*.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] British countess and mathematician Ada Lovelace is often considered to be the first computer programmer.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] She authored an algorithm, which was published in October 1842, for calculating Bernoulli numbers on the Charles Babbage analytical engine.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Because the machine was not completed in her lifetime, she never experienced the algorithm in action.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] In 1941, German civil engineer Konrad Zuse was the first person to execute a program on a working, program-controlled, electronic computer.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] From 1943 to 1945, per computer scientist Wolfgang K.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Giloi and AI professor Raúl Rojas et al., Zuse created the first, high-level programming language, Plankalkül.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Members of the 1945 ENIAC programming team of Kay McNulty, Betty Jennings, Betty Snyder, Marlyn Wescoff, Fran Bilas and Ruth Lichterman have since been credited as the first professional computer programmers.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] The first company founded specifically to provide software products and services was the Computer Usage Company in 1955.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Before that time, computers were programmed either by customers or the few commercial computer manufacturers of the time, such as Sperry Rand and IBM.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] The software industry expanded in the early 1960s, almost immediately after computers were first sold in mass-produced quantities.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Universities, governments, and businesses created a demand for software.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Many of these programs were written in-house by full-time staff programmers; some were distributed between users of a particular machine for no charge, while others were sold on a commercial basis.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Other firms, such as Computer Sciences Corporation (founded in 1959), also started to grow.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Computer manufacturers soon started bundling operating systems, system software and programming environments with their machines; the IBM 1620 came with the 1620 Symbolic Programming System and FORTRAN.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] The industry expanded greatly with the rise of the personal computer (PC) in the mid-1970s, which brought computing to the average office worker.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] In the following years, the PC also helped create a constantly growing market for games, applications and utility software.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] This resulted in increased demand for software developers for that period of time.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Computer programmers write, test, debug, and maintain the detailed instructions, called computer programs, that computers must follow to perform their functions.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Programmers also conceive, design, and test logical structures for solving problems by computer.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Many technical innovations in programming — advanced computing technologies and sophisticated new languages and programming tools — have redefined the role of a programmer and elevated much of the programming work done today.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Job titles and descriptions may vary, depending on the organization.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Programmers work in many settings, including corporate information technology (IT) departments, big software companies, small service firms and government entities of all sizes.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Many professional programmers also work for consulting companies at client sites as contractors.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Licensing is not typically required to work as a programmer, although professional certifications are commonly held by programmers.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Programming editors, also known as source code editors, are text editors that are specifically designed for programmers or developers to write the source code of an application or a program.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Most of these editors include features useful for programmers, which may include color syntax highlighting, auto indentation, auto-complete, bracket matching, syntax check, and allows plug-ins.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] These features aid the users during coding, debugging and testing.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] According to BBC News, 17% of computer science students could not find work in their field six months after graduation in 2009 which was the highest rate of the university subjects surveyed while 0% of medical students were unemployed in the same survey.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] After the crash of the dot-com bubble (1999–2001) and the Great Recession (2008), many U.S. programmers were left without work or with lower wages.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] The current prediction for 2024 to 2034 is a decline of -6 percent.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Since computer programming can be done from anywhere in the world, companies sometimes hire programmers in countries where wages are lower.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] If domestic demand has increased, it is mainly to replace the attrition of aging programmers or those leaving this occupation.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] However, for software developers BLS projects current growth at 15% that is down from their prediction from 2019 to 2029 of a 22% increase in employment, from 1,469,200 to 1,785,200 jobs with a median base salary of $110,000 per year.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] This prediction is lower than the earlier 2010 to 2020 predicted increase of 30% for software developers.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Though the distinction is somewhat ambiguous, software developers engage in a wider array of aspects of application development and are generally higher skilled than programmers, making outsourcing less of a risk.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Another reason for the decline for programmers is their skills are being merged with other professions, such as developers, as employers increase the requirements for a position over time (i.e. full-stack developer).
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] This skill consolidation has led some employers to claim there is a skills shortage with regard to programming talent.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] However, US programmers and unions counter that some are exaggerating their case in order to obtain programmers from countries with lower wages and avoid paying for training in very specific technologies.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Then there is the additional concern that recent advances in artificial intelligence and vibe coding might drastically impact the demand for future generations of Software professions.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] As of 2024 in Japan, the demand for programmers is increasing rapidly due mainly to the aging demographics of their workforce and their low birth rate not being sufficient for replacement has led to more use of AI to help fill the gap.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Programming education involves the teaching and learning of computer programming concepts, languages, and practices.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] It is offered through various formats, including formal computer science degree programs, vocational training, career and technical education centers, coding bootcamps, libraries, online courses, and self-directed learning.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Educational initiatives often focus on problem-solving, computational thinking, logical thinking, and the development of algorithms.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] In primary and secondary education, programming is increasingly integrated into computer literacy curricula through initiatives such as Hour of Code, Code Club, Learn to Code, and by getting computers in the classroom.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] At the higher education level, programming instruction may include coursework in software engineering, data structures, debugging, software design, and specialized domains such as game development, artificial intelligence, cryptography, or data science.
[src:angelika-graf/programmer] Numerous platforms and resources like AI chat bots, educational programming software, and online integrated development environments have expanded access to programming education.
